# My Idea

#### In my capstone project, I want to create a restaurant recommendation website where users can search for the best-rated restaurants in their city. The website will display restaurant names, ratings, and links to their Google Maps locations. Users will be able to filter results by cuisines such as Italian

#### Indian, Chinese, Korean, and Lebanese. Registered users can create profiles to rate restaurants directly on the platform. Each user can rate a restaurant only once but will have the option to update their rating anytime. This system

#### will prevent duplicate ratings and ensure data accuracy. The website will maintain its own database to store these ratings. The platform will also feature a "Community" section, allowing users to create or join groups to discuss dining experiences, share recommendations, and plan visits. This fosters user engagement and collaboration. By combining advanced search

#### capabilities, an accurate rating system, and a community driven approach, this project aims to provide an intuitive and reliable tool for discovering and exploring restaurants

##### perform error handling and logging without exposing internal information to the user

##### secure data storage for player account information and any personal data input

# Test and deployment plans

1. Testing Strategy

The testing process for the restaurant recommendation platform will be structured, repeatable, and automated where possible. The following testing methodologies will be applied:

- - **Unit Testing**: Ensures individual components (authentication, database queries, review submission) perform as expected.
    - **Integration Testing**: Verifies that modules work together correctly (frontend with API, database interactions).
    - **Functional Testing**: Confirms features function as required (search, filtering, rating, reviewing, discussion forums).
    - **API Testing**: Ensures backend APIs return expected results under various conditions.
    - **Security Testing**: Identifies vulnerabilities such as SQL Injection and XSS.
    - **Accessibility Testing**: Validates usability for a diverse range of users.
    - **UI Testing**: Ensures correct display and responsiveness across devices.

# Deployment Plan

- - **Frontend**: Deployed as a static site using Netlify.
    - **Backend**: Deploy the backend API using Render or CSUNIX.
    - **Database**: Use PostgreSQL on Render or CSUNIX.
    - **Image Storage**: Cloudinary (for user profile pictures and restaurant images).

1. Justification for Hosting Choice
    - **Frontend**: Free tier on Netlify for cost efficiency and performance.
    - **Backend**: Render provides free API hosting or CSUNIX as an institutional option.
    - **Database**: PostgreSQL on Render for scalability or CSUNIX for integration.
    - **Storage**: Cloudinary free tier provides image hosting at no cost.

# Reflection Description

The Value of Preparing the Proposal

Before I even start building my restaurant recommendation app, I have to write this proposal. At first, I didn’t get why it was so important—it just seemed like extra homework. But now I realize it’s like drawing a map before going on a trip. Here’s why it’s helpful:

###### It Makes Me Think Ahead

- 1. I have to figure out exactly what my app will do (like letting people rate restaurants or chat about food).
  2. If I don’t plan now, I might forget important stuff later or waste time on things I don’t need.

###### The Functionality Chart is Like a Game Plan

- 1. Breaking the project into small steps (like "Week 1: Set up login") makes it less scary.
  2. I can see which parts connect (like I need a database before people can write reviews).

###### Planning the Database Early Saves Trouble

- 1. If I design how data will be stored now (like user accounts and restaurant

info), I won’t have to redo everything later.

###### The Timeline Keeps Me from Procrastinating

- 1. Having deadlines for each part means I can’t leave everything until the last minute.
  2. The early deployment rule (by Week 8) will help me find problems before they get too big.

###### Things That Might Not Be as Useful

- **Too Many Small Details**: Spending hours planning tiny things (like button colors)

might not matter since I’ll probably change them later.

- **Overly Complicated Test Plans**: Writing super long test scripts now might not

help, since I’ll adjust them as I build.

###### How the Course Could Be Even Better

- **More Feedback from Classmates**: If other students could check my plans (like my database design), they might spot mistakes I missed.

###### A Promise to My Future Self Hey Future Me

I know you haven’t started coding yet, but here’s what I want you to remember:

###### Stick to the Plan

- 1. Follow the timeline, even when it’s boring. Small steps are better than last- minute panic!

###### Ask for Help When Stuck

- 1. Don’t sit there confused for hours—ask the teacher or classmates.

###### Test Early, Test Often

- 1. Check if things work on phones first, not just on your computer.

###### Keep Your Code Organized

- 1. Name files clearly, and don’t delete old versions—you might need them!

You’re going to learn a lot, even when it’s frustrating. Just take it one week at a time.
